00:00:23.620 --> 00:00:25.340
PROFESSOR: My first
question is, do you

00:00:25.340 --> 00:00:29.240
have any questions about
the last class, about

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:34.930
the introduction, about the
course overview, the syllabus,

00:00:34.930 --> 00:00:38.050
any requirements of the
course, formalities?

00:00:42.340 --> 00:00:44.360
It should be pretty clear.

00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:50.055
So today, we start
from first principles.

00:00:54.300 --> 00:01:03.370
I want to give you a
rigorous derivation of what

00:01:03.370 --> 00:01:07.590
this course is based,
namely, the Hamiltonian

00:01:07.590 --> 00:01:12.340
to describe the interaction
between atoms and light.

00:01:12.340 --> 00:01:15.820
I mentioned to you last
week that atomic physics can

00:01:15.820 --> 00:01:17.470
be defined about
everything that is

00:01:17.470 --> 00:01:20.560
interesting about the building
blocks of nature, atoms

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:23.040
interacting with light
electromagnetic fields, Coulomb

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:26.190
fields, and today, we'll talk
about the first principle,

00:01:26.190 --> 00:01:26.690
Hamiltonian.

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:40.770
The reference for
that, and I'm closely

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:44.070
following that derivation,
is the book Atom-Photon

00:01:44.070 --> 00:01:48.215
Interaction, the green book
by Cohen-Tannoudji, Grynberg,

00:01:48.215 --> 00:01:52.100
and others, and it's
taken from the appendix.

00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:57.360
And if you flip
through the appendix,

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:00.675
you will find out that there
are about 100 equations.

00:02:04.170 --> 00:02:08.039
Today, we'll discuss
every single of them.

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:12.020
However, the good
news is the result

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:15.720
in the end is simple
and intuitive.

00:02:22.210 --> 00:02:24.590
In the end, we
have what we want,

00:02:24.590 --> 00:02:27.870
that the electromagnetic
field couples different energy

00:02:27.870 --> 00:02:31.160
levels, and then we can play
around with quantum case,

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:32.030
with laser cooling.

00:02:32.030 --> 00:02:34.190
All we need is a
coupling matrix element.

00:02:34.190 --> 00:02:37.850
And for most of the
course, I will not even

00:02:37.850 --> 00:02:41.120
elaborate what this
matrix element is about.

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:43.480
But here, we derive it
from first principles.

00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:49.110
The result we will
use most often

00:02:49.110 --> 00:03:02.910
is actually the electric
dipole approximation,

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:09.310
which I'm sure you have
already seen many, many times.

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:15.010
So in that sense, I sometimes
have second thoughts.

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:16.950
Should I dedicate
a whole lecture

00:03:16.950 --> 00:03:19.680
to derive something
you know already?

00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:23.330
On the other hand, this is sort
of the meat of atomic physics,

00:03:23.330 --> 00:03:26.440
and I want to go
as deep as possible

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:29.140
into it, that
whenever you wonder

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:31.750
what form of other
interactions exist,

00:03:31.750 --> 00:03:33.780
you have a reference
to look it up.

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:36.780
And so to some extent,
I want to also encourage

00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:41.080
you to read more about the
fundamental nature of how light

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:42.790
and atoms interact.

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:44.890
I will give you another
reference a little bit

00:03:44.890 --> 00:03:46.820
later on.

00:03:46.820 --> 00:03:50.460
But as a motivation,
I want to tell you

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:56.520
what I learned when I
prepared this lecture,

00:03:56.520 --> 00:03:58.340
and I hope that
there is something

00:03:58.340 --> 00:04:00.400
that you will learn
from this treatment.

00:04:10.950 --> 00:04:14.785
One is a rigorous
separation of local fields

00:04:14.785 --> 00:04:16.045
from radiation fields.

00:04:22.310 --> 00:04:26.230
Let me just write it
down, rigorous separation

00:04:26.230 --> 00:04:45.115
of local Coulomb fields
from radiation fields.

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:50.820
So to clearly separate the
terms in the Hamiltonian,

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:51.653
let me explain that.

00:04:54.990 --> 00:04:57.630
When we introduce
electromagnetic fields

00:04:57.630 --> 00:05:00.560
into our world, we would
say we introduce them

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:02.990
by saying particles have charge.

00:05:02.990 --> 00:05:06.770
But some parts of the
charged particle physics

00:05:06.770 --> 00:05:12.190
is something we want to include
in the description of atoms,

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:14.310
and that's the Coulomb
field of protons.

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:16.860
The structure of atoms
is electromagnetic,

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:20.200
but when we now introduce
electromagnetic field

00:05:20.200 --> 00:05:22.310
as a new degree of
freedom-- photons

00:05:22.310 --> 00:05:24.200
can be admitted,
absorbed, and such--

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:27.450
we only want to talk about
the electric field which

00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:30.630
belongs to the photons and
not the electric field which

00:05:30.630 --> 00:05:32.230
belongs to the atoms.

00:05:32.230 --> 00:05:35.820
And you may wonder,
can you distinguish

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:38.930
between two kinds
of electric fields?

00:05:38.930 --> 00:05:42.420
The answer is yes, and I want to
show you how mathematically you

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:46.110
distinguish when you introduce
electromagnetic fields

00:05:46.110 --> 00:05:50.700
between the fields which stay
with the atom, which don't have

00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:53.960
an extra degree of
freedom, and if you

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:55.815
do canonical quantization,
they don't enter

00:05:55.815 --> 00:05:59.700
as an extra variable, and the
fields which are the photons,

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:02.543
and these are the extra
objects we have to consider.

00:06:06.170 --> 00:06:11.490
What is also related is when
you do second quantization,

00:06:11.490 --> 00:06:15.350
if you wanted, I could quantize
electromagnetic field for you

00:06:15.350 --> 00:06:16.320
in five minutes.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:18.180
Just say it's
harmonic oscillator.

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:19.888
You're familiar with
harmonic oscillator,

00:06:19.888 --> 00:06:22.390
and let's just do it.

00:06:22.390 --> 00:06:25.780
Yes, this is correct, and I will
remind you of that a little bit

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:29.660
later, but there is
one non-trivial aspect

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:34.460
if you want to do quantization
of a field theory,

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:37.040
you have to make sure that
before you quantize it,

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:41.050
you know which degrees of
freedom are really independent.

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:45.440
So the question is, how
many independent fields

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:47.530
does the electromagnetic
field have?

00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:50.920
The naive answer is three
electric field components,

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:54.030
three magnetic field
components, that makes six.

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:55.790
But of course they're
not independent,

00:06:55.790 --> 00:06:57.015
and we will discuss that.

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:07.750
So we'll spend some time
in the identification

00:07:07.750 --> 00:07:20.390
of truly independent field
components, or degrees

00:07:20.390 --> 00:07:24.530
of freedom of the
electromagnetic field.

00:07:28.970 --> 00:07:38.600
So all that is an excursion
into classical physics

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:43.830
because it is just reformulating
classical electrodynamics

00:07:43.830 --> 00:07:45.460
to be ready for quantization.

00:07:53.160 --> 00:08:00.860
Actually, all the work is
done to discuss and derive

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:02.550
the appropriate
classical description.

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:16.850
That means to eliminate
all redundant variables,

00:08:16.850 --> 00:08:19.970
and then at the end, have
variables which, yes,

00:08:19.970 --> 00:08:22.440
will look like a
harmonic oscillator.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:26.440
And once we have reduced it
to degrees of freedom which

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:33.340
look like a harmonic oscillator,
it is very straightforward

00:08:33.340 --> 00:08:38.030
to do the field
quantization following

00:08:38.030 --> 00:08:39.640
the recipe of the
harmonic oscillator.

00:08:43.260 --> 00:08:49.260
There's one more highlight,
if I want to say so,

00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:58.830
and this is a truly
rigorous derivation

00:08:58.830 --> 00:09:00.596
of the electric
dipole approximation.

00:09:07.490 --> 00:09:17.980
In most quantum
mechanics textbooks,

00:09:17.980 --> 00:09:21.240
you do a dipole
approximation and you wind up

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:24.590
with the electric dipole
Hamiltonian, which

00:09:24.590 --> 00:09:29.550
I have already put up
there, but you do actually

00:09:29.550 --> 00:09:32.460
unnecessary
approximations in terms

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:36.040
of neglecting an a squared
term, and there are often

00:09:36.040 --> 00:09:38.140
confusing discussions
what happens

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:39.720
with the a squared term.

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:42.010
I want to show you a
more rigorous deviation

00:09:42.010 --> 00:09:44.600
of the electric dipole
approximation, which

00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:50.160
is including the quadratic term.

00:09:56.130 --> 00:09:58.550
That actually means--
that's the take home

00:09:58.550 --> 00:10:02.940
message-- the electric dipole
approximation is actually

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:05.515
better than many of you
have thought so far.

00:10:12.820 --> 00:10:16.530
Since I don't want to
write out 100 equations,

00:10:16.530 --> 00:10:20.500
I copied them and summarized
them out of the book.

00:10:20.500 --> 00:10:23.050
You'll find them all,
as I mentioned before,

00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:25.850
in the appendix of
Atom-Photon Interaction.

00:10:25.850 --> 00:10:29.580
But I sort of want
to walk you through.

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:31.280
What I'm aiming at
is that you have

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:36.040
sort of a complete overview how
is everything coming together,

00:10:36.040 --> 00:10:39.060
and if it's just mathematical,
well, mathematics

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:40.320
is always exact.

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:42.890
I can go faster,
but I really want

00:10:42.890 --> 00:10:46.550
to highlight here every
single physical concept

00:10:46.550 --> 00:10:48.342
and approximation we are doing.

00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:55.330
When we start out with
Maxwell's equations,

00:10:55.330 --> 00:11:04.570
we have actually six components
of the electromagnetic field,

00:11:04.570 --> 00:11:10.720
and we will see in a moment
that this is redundant.

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:22.310
What will turn out to be
very important to separate

00:11:22.310 --> 00:11:25.190
the local fields from
the radiation field

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:38.930
is a Fourier transformation,
so we introduce an expansion

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:41.490
into plain waves.

00:11:41.490 --> 00:11:43.880
And what then
happens, of course,

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:49.400
is the derivative operator
becomes the k vector.

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:52.660
So therefore, when you
have Maxwell's equations

00:11:52.660 --> 00:12:00.050
with the curl, del cross
B, it turns into k cross

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:08.700
B. This is now important because
we have now separate equations

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:11.830
for the component of the
electric and magnetic field,

00:12:11.830 --> 00:12:16.140
which is parallel to
k, projected onto k,

00:12:16.140 --> 00:12:18.910
and of course, the
cross product takes out

00:12:18.910 --> 00:12:21.150
the component which
is perpendicular to k.

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:27.800
So that's something
which is sort of nice,

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:34.750
that the Fourier transform
it allows us to separate

00:12:34.750 --> 00:12:41.910
the fields into
longitudinal fields, where

00:12:41.910 --> 00:12:45.110
the vector of the
Fourier component

00:12:45.110 --> 00:12:52.253
is parallel to the k vector,
and into transverse components.

00:12:52.253 --> 00:12:53.169
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:13:01.812 --> 00:13:04.020
PROFESSOR: The difference
between curly and non-curly

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:05.590
vector is one is a
Fourier transform,

00:13:05.590 --> 00:13:07.630
the other one is other
spatial components.

00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:16.760
I have to actually
say the book API

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:21.350
tries to be super accurate
in choosing [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:21.350 --> 00:13:23.670
Claude Cohen-Tannoudji
is really a master

00:13:23.670 --> 00:13:25.810
of elegance and
perfection, so they

00:13:25.810 --> 00:13:28.270
don't want to use
the same [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:28.270 --> 00:13:32.190
for a spatial component and
for the Fourier component.

00:13:32.190 --> 00:13:34.910
On the other hand, I have
to tell you one thing.

00:13:34.910 --> 00:13:37.790
For the next hour, use a
little bit your intuition.

00:13:37.790 --> 00:13:40.790
If you see e, it
means electric field.

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:43.290
Whether it is curly,
whether it's italic,

00:13:43.290 --> 00:13:47.450
whether it's bold
face, don't let

00:13:47.450 --> 00:13:50.130
those differences
clutter your view.

00:13:50.130 --> 00:13:52.890
So I would say don't
ask me too often,

00:13:52.890 --> 00:13:55.320
what exactly does it
mean now because you

00:13:55.320 --> 00:13:58.720
have gone from
curly to non-curly?

00:13:58.720 --> 00:14:00.750
It is explained in the appendix.

00:14:00.750 --> 00:14:03.350
I will tell you everything
which is necessary,

00:14:03.350 --> 00:14:08.210
but these are
subtleties which are

00:14:08.210 --> 00:14:12.620
more to present the mathematics
in a more rigorous way.

00:14:16.300 --> 00:14:19.420
We have the spatial
Fourier components,

00:14:19.420 --> 00:14:27.300
and as I mentioned, what you can
do only because of the Fourier

00:14:27.300 --> 00:14:38.756
transform, you have
now the distinction,

00:14:38.756 --> 00:14:49.180
a rigorous separation
between the parallel

00:14:49.180 --> 00:14:50.346
and the longitudinal fields.

00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:11.090
So of course, you
can also now get back

00:15:11.090 --> 00:15:14.900
what is the longitudinal
field, not in Fourier space

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:18.460
but in position
space, by just taking

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:23.000
the longitudinal or transverse
components of the Fourier

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.290
transform and
transforming them back.

00:15:25.290 --> 00:15:27.300
Why I'm elaborating
on that is we

00:15:27.300 --> 00:15:30.510
will see in the next few minutes
that the transverse field

00:15:30.510 --> 00:15:32.200
is the field which propagates.

00:15:32.200 --> 00:15:34.720
The longitudinal field
is the Coulomb field.

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:37.080
It belongs to the
atoms and will not

00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:38.830
become a new degree of freedom.

00:15:42.710 --> 00:15:48.150
And we see that immediately
in the next equations.

00:15:48.150 --> 00:15:56.270
When we look now at
Maxwell's equations,

00:15:56.270 --> 00:16:00.890
we find that the transverse and
longitudinal fields decouple.

00:16:00.890 --> 00:16:06.810
We have two kinds of equations
which are completely decoupled.

00:16:06.810 --> 00:16:11.890
The longitudinal electric field
is the Coulomb field associated

00:16:11.890 --> 00:16:17.210
with a charge density, whereas
the transverse fields are

00:16:17.210 --> 00:16:20.710
creating themselves,
and this is radiation,

00:16:20.710 --> 00:16:23.675
how the electric and magnetic
fields create themselves

00:16:23.675 --> 00:16:24.425
as they propagate.

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:46.200
Now, the fact that the
parallel electric field

00:16:46.200 --> 00:16:52.790
can be expressed by
the charge density,

00:16:52.790 --> 00:17:06.930
or it's expressed by the
momentary position of charges,

00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:14.079
and this means immediately that
the longitudinal field is not

00:17:14.079 --> 00:17:18.169
an independent variable or
an extra degree of freedom.

00:17:23.619 --> 00:17:25.514
Canonical, of course,
with how we describe

00:17:25.514 --> 00:17:29.680
particles by their position,
and here you see explicitly

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:33.350
that the longitudinal
field which

00:17:33.350 --> 00:17:39.850
we defined the way we did it,
that this part of the field

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:44.124
only depends on the momentarily
electric field, the Coulomb

00:17:44.124 --> 00:17:45.540
field associated
with the charges.

00:18:03.810 --> 00:18:06.480
The next thing, of course,
is to define the vector

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:13.080
potential and the
scalar potential.

00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:20.640
By using the standard
substitution,

00:18:20.640 --> 00:18:23.670
we can now express electric
and magnetic fields

00:18:23.670 --> 00:18:26.735
by a scalar potential and
by a vector potential.

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:37.050
We continue to
have the separation

00:18:37.050 --> 00:18:40.570
between longitudinal
and transverse fields,

00:18:40.570 --> 00:18:49.210
namely the transverse
electromagnetic fields

00:18:49.210 --> 00:18:53.700
depend only on the
transverse component

00:18:53.700 --> 00:18:54.700
of the vector potential.

00:18:59.530 --> 00:19:04.860
And the transverse component
is gauge invariant.

00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:11.910
In other words, you know
there are different gauges we

00:19:11.910 --> 00:19:15.050
can consider when we introduce
electromagnetic potentials,

00:19:15.050 --> 00:19:20.000
but the choice of gauge does
not affect the transverse vector

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:20.500
potential.

00:19:27.530 --> 00:19:31.190
Now we want to pick
our gauge and repeat

00:19:31.190 --> 00:19:33.820
the gauge which is
most convenient.

00:19:33.820 --> 00:19:38.200
This is typically, for low
energy quantum physics,

00:19:38.200 --> 00:19:42.380
for describing atoms and
radiation, the Coulomb gauge.

00:19:42.380 --> 00:19:45.700
So we have the freedom of
gauge, and the Coulomb gauge

00:19:45.700 --> 00:19:53.075
is written by the divergence
of the vector potential is 0.

00:19:55.680 --> 00:19:58.800
If you now think about
Fourier transform,

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:03.130
this means k dot the
Fourier component is 0,

00:20:03.130 --> 00:20:07.230
and that means the
vector potential does not

00:20:07.230 --> 00:20:09.020
have any longitudinal component.

00:20:21.070 --> 00:20:33.660
So with that, we have
now reduced equations

00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:36.860
for six variables, three
electric fields, three

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:38.640
magnetic field components.

00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:43.200
By introducing vector and scalar
potential, you go to four.

00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:46.230
We've eliminated one more
with the Coulomb gauge,

00:20:46.230 --> 00:20:48.780
so we have three.

00:20:48.780 --> 00:20:51.400
The scalar potential is
the Coulomb potential.

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:53.170
It's not an extra
degree of freedom.

00:20:53.170 --> 00:21:02.320
And what is left are
the two field components

00:21:02.320 --> 00:21:04.050
of the transverse
vector potential.

00:21:14.630 --> 00:21:29.112
And these are now, as we will
see, the independent variables

00:21:29.112 --> 00:21:30.890
of the radiation field.

00:21:36.730 --> 00:21:39.440
So in other words, when we talk
about the electromagnetic field

00:21:39.440 --> 00:21:42.550
in the remainder of
the course, the part

00:21:42.550 --> 00:21:45.580
of the electromagnetic
field we are interested in

00:21:45.580 --> 00:21:49.450
are the fields generated by the
transverse vector potential.

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:10.960
Now, what is next is to
go into normal modes.

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:15.310
The reason is that
we want to identify

00:22:15.310 --> 00:22:18.680
each normal mode of the
electromagnetic field

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:21.760
as an independent
harmonic oscillator.

00:22:21.760 --> 00:22:24.680
Now, I'm showing
you those equations,

00:22:24.680 --> 00:22:30.960
but you sort of have to sit
